				<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="544"> 
					<tr>
						<td><b>Ingredients</b></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="10" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr>
						<td>5 Chinese cabbages (15kg), 2<img src="images/half.gif" border="0" align="absmiddle" vspace="2">radish,<br>watercress 1 bunch (300g), leaf mustard  <img src="images/half.gif" border="0" align="absmiddle" vspace="2">bunch (500g), spring onions  <img src="images/half.gif" border="0" align="absmiddle" vspace="2">bunch (200g), green onion  <img src="images/half.gif" border="0" align="absmiddle" vspace="2">bunch (200g), raw oyster 300g, raw shrimp 1 C(150g), 5 whole garlics (200g), 2 whole gingers (50g), salt-fermented shrimp  <img src="images/half.gif" border="0" align="absmiddle" vspace="2">C, salt-fermented croakers liquid  <img src="images/half.gif" border="0" align="absmiddle" vspace="2">C (100g), salts, sugar</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="10" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>Salt water: salt 1.5kg, water 7 L</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="20" border="0"></td></tr>
				</table>
				
				<!-- -->
				<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="544"> 
					<tr>
						<td colspan="2"><b>Directions</b></td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="10" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td width="15">1)</td>
						<td>Trim the Chinese cabbage, and cut into 2 pieces. Put in a large pot with the cross sections upward, and pour in 9% salt water. Press the cabbage with something heavy so that it is submerged in the salt water.</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>2)</td>
						<td>Drain the salted down cabbages, wash, and put on a basket with cross sections down so that the water comes off. If the cabbage is too big, cut it in half again, and remove the roots.</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>3)</td>
						<td>Mix shredded radish with red pepper powder until it's tinged red. Add watercress, leaf mustard, spring onions, green onions, garlic, ginger, and salt-fermented seafoods with liquid and mix well. If the seasonging of ingredients tastes too weak, add more salt and sugar. Mix them with raw oyster and raw shrimps.</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>4)</td>
						<td>Place a small amount of mixed ingredients between leaves of salted Chinese cabbage evenly, wrap it with the biggest leaf to keep ingredients from falling, and put it in an earthenware Kimchi pot. Place a large outer cabbage leaf on the top and press the whole with a clean rock. If liquid is little, boil water and season it with salt or liquid of salt-fermented seafoods, and pour.</td>
					</tr>
					<tr><td colspan="2"><img src="/common/images/trans.gif" width="1" height="7" border="0"></td></tr>
					<tr valign="top">
						<td>5)</td>
						<td>After 3 weeks, it is fermented enough to eat.</td>
					</tr>
